{"data":{"post":{"id":"7f92a5ba-ff05-5ba8-8bee-618c30692f08","html":"<p>It is hard to imagine a world without Monet and his water lilies, and so much more without <strong>Edgar Degas and his ballerinas</strong>. Ever since I saw Degas’ works at the <a href=\"http://www.musee-orsay.fr/en/home.html\" title=\"Musee d&#x27;Orsay\">Musee d’ Orsay</a>, I was introduced to a <strong>fascinating behind-the-scenes world of ballet dancers</strong>, which were more interesting than the actual spectacle.  </p>\n<p>Clearly, <strong>ballet was the domain of Edgar Degas</strong>, who was known to be a fixture of the Paris Opera in the late 19th century in his attempt to capture movement and beauty. But in this exhibit at the <a href=\"http://www.royalacademy.org.uk/exhibitions/degas/about-the-exhibition/\" title=\"Royal academy of art: Degas\">Royal Academy of Art</a>, there was so much more about Degas that I didn’t know. I expected only to be bombarded by images of ballerinas, but <strong>the exhibit also focused on his creative process and his experimentation with the technological advances</strong> of his time.</p>\n<div>\n          <div\n            class=\"gatsby-resp-iframe-wrapper\"\n            style=\"padding-bottom: 78.90625%; position: relative; height: 0; overflow: hidden;margin-bottom: 2em\"\n          >\n            <iframe allowfullscreen class=\"youtube-player\" frameborder=\"0\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/sNHkujPaibY?wmode=transparent&amp;fs=1&amp;hl=en&amp;modestbranding=1&amp;iv_load_policy=3&amp;showsearch=0&amp;rel=0&amp;theme=dark\" title=\"YouTube video player\" type=\"text/html\" style=\"\n            position: absolute;\n            top: 0;\n            left: 0;\n            width: 100%;\n            height: 100%;\n          \"></iframe>\n          </div>\n          </div>\n<figcaption>Ann Dumas of the Royal Academy</figcaption>\n<p><strong>The genius of Degas is of course his way of capturing special and unguarded moments.</strong> Just look at the many images of ballet dancers slumped in a corner or when they are just in repose such as in the <strong>Dance Lesson and the Dance rehearsal</strong>. He captured this essence of spontaneity but <strong>framed the scenes asymmetrically allowing us an experience of seeing it mid-scene</strong>. The composition of his paintings made me wonder whether he was sketching or fiddling with an advanced camera with a fantastic element of depth of field to record these scenes before actually painting them.</p>\n<p>\n  <figure class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figure\" style=\"\">\n  \n  <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/momardi/static/627201ab448c80953e51f15fd5989203/55fd7/Degas_the-dance-lesson_gvclqc.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n    style=\"position: relative; display: block;  max-width: 640px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\"\n  >\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n      style=\"padding-bottom: 42.96875%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n    >\n      <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        style=\"width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px transparent;\"\n        alt=\"Degas the dance lesson gvclqc\"\n        title=\"Edgar Degas: The Dance Lesson, c. 1879. Oil on canvas. 38 x 88 cm. National Gallery of Art, Washington. Collection of Mr. and Mrs. Paul Mellon, 1995.47.6. Photo National Gallery of Art, Washington\"\n        src=\"/momardi/static/627201ab448c80953e51f15fd5989203/55fd7/Degas_the-dance-lesson_gvclqc.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/momardi/static/627201ab448c80953e51f15fd5989203/e81c0/Degas_the-dance-lesson_gvclqc.jpg 200w,\n/momardi/static/627201ab448c80953e51f15fd5989203/8e8ea/Degas_the-dance-lesson_gvclqc.jpg 400w,\n/momardi/static/627201ab448c80953e51f15fd5989203/55fd7/Degas_the-dance-lesson_gvclqc.jpg 640w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px\"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    \n  <figcaption class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figcaption\">Edgar Degas: The Dance Lesson, c. 1879. Oil on canvas. 38 x 88 cm. National Gallery of Art, Washington. Collection of Mr. and Mrs. Paul Mellon, 1995.47.6. Photo National Gallery of Art, Washington</figcaption>\n  </figure>\n      </p>\n<p>\n  <figure class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figure\" style=\"\">\n  \n  <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/momardi/static/f654f20049ec892a3379aee1f8b29ad6/55fd7/Degas_the-rehearsal_xwlcrg.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n    style=\"position: relative; display: block;  max-width: 640px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\"\n  >\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n      style=\"padding-bottom: 67.8125%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n    >\n      <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        style=\"width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px transparent;\"\n        alt=\"Degas the rehearsal xwlcrg\"\n        title=\"Edgar Degas: The Rehearsal, c. 1874. Oil on canvas, 58.4 x 83.8 cm. Lent by Culture and Sport Glasgow on behalf of Glasgow City Council. Gifted by Sir William and Lady Constance Burrell to the City of Glasgow, 1944. Image copyright Culture and Sport Glasgow (Museums)\"\n        src=\"/momardi/static/f654f20049ec892a3379aee1f8b29ad6/55fd7/Degas_the-rehearsal_xwlcrg.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/momardi/static/f654f20049ec892a3379aee1f8b29ad6/e81c0/Degas_the-rehearsal_xwlcrg.jpg 200w,\n/momardi/static/f654f20049ec892a3379aee1f8b29ad6/8e8ea/Degas_the-rehearsal_xwlcrg.jpg 400w,\n/momardi/static/f654f20049ec892a3379aee1f8b29ad6/55fd7/Degas_the-rehearsal_xwlcrg.jpg 640w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px\"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    \n  <figcaption class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figcaption\">Edgar Degas: The Rehearsal, c. 1874. Oil on canvas, 58.4 x 83.8 cm. Lent by Culture and Sport Glasgow on behalf of Glasgow City Council. Gifted by Sir William and Lady Constance Burrell to the City of Glasgow, 1944. Image copyright Culture and Sport Glasgow (Museums)</figcaption>\n  </figure>\n      </p>\n<p><strong>He was obsessed with human figure movement and choreography</strong>. Degas, however, couldn’t find alliance with his Impressionists friends to share this new passion except for the photographers which eventually led him to photography. There were <strong>three photographs he shot of three ballet dancers</strong> which showed his interest in lighting effects. There was also a photo of a woman in a bathtub which was the inspiration for the famous bathtub painting.</p>\n<p>The exhibit even went so far as including a clip <strong>(Serpentine Dance) from the Lumiere brothers</strong> and displaying items such as plate cameras which were a novelty during that time. <strong>Ann Dumas</strong>, curator of the Royal Academy of Art said these films were frequently shown in Montmarte and Degas would have certainly known about them.</p>\n<div>\n          <div\n            class=\"gatsby-resp-iframe-wrapper\"\n            style=\"padding-bottom: 78.90625%; position: relative; height: 0; overflow: hidden;margin-bottom: 2em\"\n          >\n            <iframe allowfullscreen class=\"youtube-player\" frameborder=\"0\" src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/kjIvOc6szZ8?wmode=transparent&amp;fs=1&amp;hl=en&amp;modestbranding=1&amp;iv_load_policy=3&amp;showsearch=0&amp;rel=0&amp;theme=dark\" title=\"YouTube video player\" type=\"text/html\" style=\"\n            position: absolute;\n            top: 0;\n            left: 0;\n            width: 100%;\n            height: 100%;\n          \"></iframe>\n          </div>\n          </div>\n<figcaption>Serpentine Dance from the Lumiere brothers, 1899</figcaption>\n<p><strong>The fantastic array of sketches included in the show also demonstrated his dedication of studying movement</strong>. With photography as his new ally, he pushed boundaries in his art and translated himself in a variety of medium – oil painting, pastels and sculpture.</p>\n<p>\n  <figure class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figure\" style=\"\">\n  \n  <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/momardi/static/169ccfc5739297b506ee60770ffd0844/33e24/Degas_dancer-charcoal_i6nkfl.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n    style=\"position: relative; display: block;  max-width: 480px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\"\n  >\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n      style=\"padding-bottom: 150.41666666666666%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n    >\n      <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        style=\"width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px transparent;\"\n        alt=\"Degas dancer charcoal i6nkfl\"\n        title=\"Dancer (Preparation en dedans), c. 1880-85. Charcoal with stumping on buff paper, 336 x 227 mm. Trinity House, London and New York\"\n        src=\"/momardi/static/169ccfc5739297b506ee60770ffd0844/33e24/Degas_dancer-charcoal_i6nkfl.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/momardi/static/169ccfc5739297b506ee60770ffd0844/7084e/Degas_dancer-charcoal_i6nkfl.jpg 200w,\n/momardi/static/169ccfc5739297b506ee60770ffd0844/e263b/Degas_dancer-charcoal_i6nkfl.jpg 400w,\n/momardi/static/169ccfc5739297b506ee60770ffd0844/33e24/Degas_dancer-charcoal_i6nkfl.jpg 480w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 480px) 100vw, 480px\"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    \n  <figcaption class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figcaption\">Dancer (Preparation en dedans), c. 1880-85. Charcoal with stumping on buff paper, 336 x 227 mm. Trinity House, London and New York</figcaption>\n  </figure>\n      </p>\n<p>\n  <figure class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figure\" style=\"\">\n  \n  <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/momardi/static/34f445131fa89d7c006b614619924f99/33e24/Degas_little-dancer_rndalm.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n    style=\"position: relative; display: block;  max-width: 480px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\"\n  >\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n      style=\"padding-bottom: 128.125%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n    >\n      <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        style=\"width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px transparent;\"\n        alt=\"Degas little dancer rndalm\"\n        title=\"Edgar Degas: The Little Dancer, Aged Fourteen, 1880-1, cast c. 1922. Painted bronze with muslin and silk, 98.4 x 36.5 cm. Tate. Purchased with assistance from The Art Fund 1952. Image copyright Tate, London, 2010\"\n        src=\"/momardi/static/34f445131fa89d7c006b614619924f99/33e24/Degas_little-dancer_rndalm.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/momardi/static/34f445131fa89d7c006b614619924f99/7084e/Degas_little-dancer_rndalm.jpg 200w,\n/momardi/static/34f445131fa89d7c006b614619924f99/e263b/Degas_little-dancer_rndalm.jpg 400w,\n/momardi/static/34f445131fa89d7c006b614619924f99/33e24/Degas_little-dancer_rndalm.jpg 480w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 480px) 100vw, 480px\"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    \n  <figcaption class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figcaption\">Edgar Degas: The Little Dancer, Aged Fourteen, 1880-1, cast c. 1922. Painted bronze with muslin and silk, 98.4 x 36.5 cm. Tate. Purchased with assistance from The Art Fund 1952. Image copyright Tate, London, 2010</figcaption>\n  </figure>\n      </p>\n<p>The only sculpture he exhibited during his lifetime, the Little Dancer was a central piece of the show. The way people inspected the <strong>Little Dancer</strong> in the exhibit, <strong>I forgot how much this sculpture had been criticized and called ugly and a monkey</strong>. There were a whole lot more of figurative sculptures in the room, and I wonder if the criticism on Little Dancer led him to practice sculpture privately. The exhibit ends with a short clip of <strong>Degas captured in film</strong>, walking in Paris with a lady.</p>\n<div>\n          <div\n            class=\"gatsby-resp-iframe-wrapper\"\n            style=\"padding-bottom: 56.25%; position: relative; height: 0; overflow: hidden;margin-bottom: 2em\"\n          >\n            <iframe src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/KET94NlM7Ys\" frameborder=\"0\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture\" allowfullscreen style=\"\n            position: absolute;\n            top: 0;\n            left: 0;\n            width: 100%;\n            height: 100%;\n          \"></iframe>\n          </div>\n          </div>\n<figcaption>Film clip of Edgar Degas</figcaption>\n<p>\n  <figure class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figure\" style=\"\">\n  \n  <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/momardi/static/7c0b46b608566657124b9ccb48f31493/33e24/Degas_dancers_q3gpcq.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n    style=\"position: relative; display: block;  max-width: 480px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\"\n  >\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n      style=\"padding-bottom: 125.62499999999999%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n    >\n      <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        style=\"width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px transparent;\"\n        alt=\"Degas dancers q3gpcq\"\n        title=\"Edgar Degas: Dancers, c. 1899. Pastel on tracing paper laid down on board, 588 x 463 mm. Princeton University Art Museum. Bequest of Henry K. Dick, Class of 1909. Image Bruce M. White\"\n        src=\"/momardi/static/7c0b46b608566657124b9ccb48f31493/33e24/Degas_dancers_q3gpcq.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/momardi/static/7c0b46b608566657124b9ccb48f31493/7084e/Degas_dancers_q3gpcq.jpg 200w,\n/momardi/static/7c0b46b608566657124b9ccb48f31493/e263b/Degas_dancers_q3gpcq.jpg 400w,\n/momardi/static/7c0b46b608566657124b9ccb48f31493/33e24/Degas_dancers_q3gpcq.jpg 480w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 480px) 100vw, 480px\"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    \n  <figcaption class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figcaption\">Edgar Degas: Dancers, c. 1899. Pastel on tracing paper laid down on board, 588 x 463 mm. Princeton University Art Museum. Bequest of Henry K. Dick, Class of 1909. Image Bruce M. White</figcaption>\n  </figure>\n      </p>\n<p>\n  <figure class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figure\" style=\"\">\n  \n  <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/momardi/static/144c7e7dd755667929169b7c612aca5d/33e24/Degas_la-danse-grecque_kjjdmz.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n    style=\"position: relative; display: block;  max-width: 480px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\"\n  >\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n      style=\"padding-bottom: 121.45833333333333%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n    >\n      <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        style=\"width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px transparent;\"\n        alt=\"Degas la danse grecque kjjdmz\"\n        title=\"Edgar Degas: La Danse Grecque (Dancing Ballerinas), 1885-90. Pastel on joined paper laid down on board, 580 x 490 mm. On loan from the Honorable Earle I. Mack Collection\"\n        src=\"/momardi/static/144c7e7dd755667929169b7c612aca5d/33e24/Degas_la-danse-grecque_kjjdmz.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/momardi/static/144c7e7dd755667929169b7c612aca5d/7084e/Degas_la-danse-grecque_kjjdmz.jpg 200w,\n/momardi/static/144c7e7dd755667929169b7c612aca5d/e263b/Degas_la-danse-grecque_kjjdmz.jpg 400w,\n/momardi/static/144c7e7dd755667929169b7c612aca5d/33e24/Degas_la-danse-grecque_kjjdmz.jpg 480w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 480px) 100vw, 480px\"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    \n  <figcaption class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figcaption\">Edgar Degas: La Danse Grecque (Dancing Ballerinas), 1885-90. Pastel on joined paper laid down on board, 580 x 490 mm. On loan from the Honorable Earle I. Mack Collection</figcaption>\n  </figure>\n      </p>\n<p>\n  <figure class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figure\" style=\"\">\n  \n  <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/momardi/static/ac1d95e2383114a2492f488ce07e05c3/55fd7/Degas_ballet-scene_nobapv.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n    style=\"position: relative; display: block;  max-width: 640px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\"\n  >\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n      style=\"padding-bottom: 92.96875%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n    >\n      <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        style=\"width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px transparent;\"\n        alt=\"Degas ballet scene nobapv\"\n        title=\"Edgar Degas: Ballet Scene from Meyerbeer’s Opera ‘Robert le Diable’, 1876. Oil on canvas, 76.6 x 81.3 cm. Victoria & Albert Museum, London. Image copyright V&A Images / Victoria and Albert Museum, London\"\n        src=\"/momardi/static/ac1d95e2383114a2492f488ce07e05c3/55fd7/Degas_ballet-scene_nobapv.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/momardi/static/ac1d95e2383114a2492f488ce07e05c3/e81c0/Degas_ballet-scene_nobapv.jpg 200w,\n/momardi/static/ac1d95e2383114a2492f488ce07e05c3/8e8ea/Degas_ballet-scene_nobapv.jpg 400w,\n/momardi/static/ac1d95e2383114a2492f488ce07e05c3/55fd7/Degas_ballet-scene_nobapv.jpg 640w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px\"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    \n  <figcaption class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figcaption\">Edgar Degas: Ballet Scene from Meyerbeer’s Opera ‘Robert le Diable’, 1876. Oil on canvas, 76.6 x 81.3 cm. Victoria & Albert Museum, London. Image copyright V&A Images / Victoria and Albert Museum, London</figcaption>\n  </figure>\n      </p>\n<p>Related Links:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/art/art-reviews/8758374/Degas-and-the-Ballet-Picturing-Movement-Royal-Academy-of-Arts-review.html\" title=\"Degas by Alastair Sooke\">Degas and the Ballet Picturing Movement by Alastair Sooke for the Telegraph</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/artanddesign/gallery/2011/sep/12/degas-ballet-movement-in-pictures\" title=\"Degas and Ballet in pictures: Guardian\">Degas and the Ballet in Pictures from the Guardian</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/24/arts/24iht-melikian24.html?_r=1&#x26;ref=royalacademyofarts\" title=\"Degas from the New York Times\">Degas: More than Just a Ballet Master by Souren Milikian for the New York Times</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/04/arts/dance/degass-ballet-at-the-phillips-collection-and-royal-academy.html?ref=royalacademyofarts\" title=\"Alastair Macaulay for the New York Times\">Workers wearing Toehoes by Alastair Macaulay for the New York Times</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/artanddesign/2011/sep/07/edgar-degas-ballet-royal-academy\" title=\"Degas: James Davidson\">A Fine Balance: Degas and the art of ballet by James Davidson for the Guardian</a></li>\n</ul>","fields":{"slug":"/degas-more-than-just-a-genius-of-movement/","prefix":"2011-10-15"},"frontmatter":{"title":"Degas: More than Just a Genius of Movement","category":"artists","cover":{"childImageSharp":{"resize":{"src":"/momardi/static/627201ab448c80953e51f15fd5989203/d927d/Degas_the-dance-lesson_gvclqc.jpg"}}}}},"authornote":{"id":"b6415c02-57f6-5889-8910-a05deb06efca","html":"<p>Article by <strong>Tuesday Gutierrez</strong>. Former digital marketing manager for the London 2012 Festival, the largest UK festival ever staged. This is her blog about contemporary art, design, film, photography and all that move her soul.</p>"}},"pageContext":{"slug":"/degas-more-than-just-a-genius-of-movement/","prev":{"id":"b7df540c-952b-5db0-b45c-837495308c69","fields":{"slug":"/over-and-out-the-end-of-the-shape-of-things-to-come-at-the-saatchi/","prefix":"2011-10-10","source":"posts"},"frontmatter":{"title":"Over and Out: The End of The Shape of Things to Come at the Saatchi","category":"exhibits"}},"next":{"id":"e893c5d5-67be-5bf5-a5b7-d41b4dc64ff4","fields":{"slug":"/rig-the-anti-monumental-and-ambiguous-phyllida-barlow-at-the-hauser-wirth/","prefix":"2011-10-20","source":"posts"},"frontmatter":{"title":"Rig: The Anti-Monumental and Ambiguous Phyllida Barlow at the Hauser & Wirth","category":"exhibits"}},"source":"posts"}}